But, if I try to use external tool, query already working, see attached screen.

{quote}
I can't speak for other platforms, but with my current setup trying to do {{[$set => ["TestInt" => 4294967295]]}} will save an Int32 in the database with value -1 (so it wraps around instead of truncating). 
{quote}

{quote}
{{$inc}} suffers from the same problem as {{$set}}. That is, if I try to {{[$inc => ["TestInt" => 4294967295]]}} I will actually subtract 1 from TestInt. Further testing has revealed that queries suffer from the same problem: If I were to make a query with a filter like {{"TestInt" => ['$lt' => 4294967295]}}, I'll actually be looking for documents where TestInt is less than -1.
{quote}

Truncation of 64-bit integers when converting BSON to PHP values may also result in property name corruption (see PHPC-592).

{quote}
It seems that I lied when I proclaimed that reading an Int64 from the db is fine. It turns out that it comes back as a string and is liable to have its property name mangled.

With the following test document:

{noformat}
{ 
    "_id" : ObjectId("569d015eb26caf586174252a"), 
    "TestObj" : {
        "Slots" : NumberLong(-429496729552)
    }
}
{noformat}

if I fetch it in php and then var_dump the result, I get:

{noformat}
object(stdClass)#13 (2) {
  ["_id"]=>
  object(MongoDB\BSON\ObjectID)#11 (1) {
    ["oid"]=>
    string(24) "569d015eb26caf586174252a"
  }
  ["TestObj"]=>
  object(stdClass)#12 (1) {
    ["Slots0"]=>
    string(13) "-429496729552"
  }
}
{noformat}

Notice that "Slots" became "Slots0". The appended characters seem to depend on the combination of property name and integer value. With the right values you can end up with invalid UTF8.
{quote}

This appears to be caused by the {{ADD_ASSOC_INT64()}} compatibility macro, which is called from {{php_phongo_bson_visit_int64()}}. That macro relies on {{ADD_ASSOC_STRINGL()}}, which in turn uses {{ZEND_STRL()}} and calculates the property string's length using [{{sizeof(str)-1}}|http://lxr.php.net/xref/PHP_5_6/Zend/zend.h#574]. This makes it suitable only for string literals and not the {{const char *}} passed through libbson's visitor function. Currently, the pointer size is being used to derive the string length.

